definition.value: Any substance that inhibits the release of insulin
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of alcohol oxidase.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of cystathionine-beta-synthase.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of mitochondrial carnitine palmitoyltransferase-1.
An inhibitor that interferes with the process of T-cell proliferation.
A small protein-like chain designed to mimic a peptide.
The element or compound in a reduction-oxidation (redox) reaction that donates an electron to another species.
A substance that removes electrons from another reactant in a redox reaction.
Any substance that inhibits the action of sodium-dependent Pi-transporters.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of alkaline phosphatase.
An antagonist at the fibroblast growth factor receptor.
A substance capable of undergoing rapid and highly exothermic decomposition.
Any acid anhydride hydrolase inhibitor that inhibits the action of  Na(+)/K(+)-transporting ATPase (EC 3.6.3.9).
Any drug which binds to gonadotropin-releasing hormone receptors and triggers a response.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a glucocorticoid receptor.
An antogonist that blocks chemokine receptor 5 (CCR5).
Any compound that inhibits the action of thymidylate synthase.
Any compound that inhibits the action of glycinamide ribonucleotide formyltransferase.
Any compound that can be used for the treatment of neurodegenerative disorders.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a retinoid X receptor.
Any compound that leaves a pliable, cohesive, and continuous covering over a surface when applied to it.

A sclerotherapy agent is used to treat blood vessels or blood vessel malformations (vascular malformations) and also those of the lymphatic system by injection into the vessels, which makes them shrink.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of tyrosine 3-monooxygenase.
An antagonist at the alpha1B-adrenoceptor.
An agonist at the estrogen receptor.
An antagonist at the A1 receptor.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the synthesis of cellulose.
An inhibitor that blocks the action of heat shock protein 90.
An antagonist at the metabotropic glutamate receptor.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a protein kinase C receptor
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of arachidonoylethanolamide amidohydrolase.
Any substance which is added to food to preserve or enhance its flavour and/or appearance.
A food additive that is used to change or otherwise control the acidity and alkalinity of foods. They may be acids, bases, neutralising agents or bufffering agents.

Any compound that mimics the action of incretins, gastrointestinal hormones that cause an increase in the amount of insulin released from the beta cells of the islets of Langerhans after eating, even before blood glucose levels become elevated.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates AMPA receptors.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a protein kinase G receptor.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a protein kinase receptor.
Enzyme inhibitor of protein farnesyltransferase (EC 2.5.1.58), one of the three enzymes in the prenyltransferase group.
Any protease inhibitor that restricts the action of a cysteine protease.
A histamine agonist that binds to and activates histamine H3-receptors.
A histamine agonist that binds to and activates H4-receptors.
A histamine antagonist that selectively binds to but does not activate histamine H3 receptors, thereby blocking the actions of endogenous histamine.

An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits any of the bacterial and eukaryote phosphotransferases, preventing formation of N-acetylglucosamine lipid intermediates and glycosylation of newly synthesised glycoproteins.
Any chemical substance produced during the conversion of a reactant to a product.
A compound which acts as an agonist at the ATP-sensitive K+ channel.

A compound used to form the matrix for MALDI (matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization) mass spectrometry. MALDI matrix materials are crystalline compounds with a fairly low molecular weight, so as to allow facile vaporization, have strong absorption at UV or IR wavelengths (to rapidly and efficiently absorb laser irradiation), generally contain polar groups (enabling them to be used in aqueous solutions) and are frequently acidic (so assisting ionisation of the compound being studied, which is contained within the matrix material).
A neurotransmitter transporter modulator that activates glutamate transporters.
A membrane transport modulator that affects the transport of neurotransmitters.
